  {
    "objectID": "topik/todaysbartle/chapter/chapter5/chapter5.1/5.1.3.html",
    "href": "topik/todaysbartle/chapter/chapter5/chapter5.1/5.1.3.html",
    "title": "5.1.3",
    "section": "",
    "text": "Let \\(a &lt; b &lt; c\\). Suppose that \\(f\\) is continuous on \\([a, b]\\), that \\(g\\) is continuous on \\([b, c]\\), and that \\(f(b) = g(b)\\). Define \\(h\\) on \\([a,c]\\) by \\(h(x) := f(x)\\) for \\(x \\in [a, b]\\) and \\(h(x) = := g(x)\\) for \\(x \\in [b,c]\\). Prove that \\(h\\) is continuous on \\([a, c]\\)\nAnswer\nPreliminary Analysis\nNotice that \\(h(x) = \\begin{cases}\n    f(x) & x \\in [a,b] \\\\\n    g(x) & x \\in [b,c]\n\\end{cases}\\).\nThus for \\([a,b]\\), \\(h\\) continuous because \\(f\\) continuous, and for \\([b,c]\\), \\(h\\) continuous because \\(g\\) continuous. Also, because \\(f(b) = g(b)\\), then it follows that \\(h(b) = f(b) = g(b)\\) which implies that \\(h\\) continuous at \\(x = b\\). Therefore \\(h\\) continuous on \\([a,c]\\) \\\nFormal Proof\n\\(h\\) continuous on \\([a,c]\\) because \\(h\\) continuous on \\([a,b]\\) and \\([b,c]\\)"
  },
